✅ Production-Level Kubernetes Cluster Upgrade Strategy (EKS Example)

1. Pre-Upgrade Preparation
   1.1 Take backup - Backup etcd (for self-managed cluster)
   1.2 Backup Kubernetes manifests (kubectl get all -A -o yaml), Helm values, Persistent Volumes (EBS snapshots), RDS
   1.3 Check Compatibility Matrix - API deprecations, Removed features, CRD compatibility
   1.4 Ensure application version supports new k8s version

2. Read Release Notes
   2.1 Deprecated APIs, PodSecurityAdmissions
   2.2 Ingress API version changes, Admission controller changes

3. Perform Upgrade in Staging Environment
   3.1 Ensure Pod scheduling, Load balance, Auto scaling, CI/CD pipeline
   3.2 Deploy sample workloads

4. Ensure Pod Disruption Budget (PDB)
   4.1 During node drain, pods must reschedule safely.
   4.2 Avoid downtime for critical services. (minavailable:1)

5. Upgrade Control Plane
   5.1 Control plane upgrade is managed by AWS. Monitor [cluster status, Events, CloudWatch logs]
   5.2 Control plane upgrade does not cause downtime, but workloads must be compatible.

6. Upgrade Node Groups (Worker Nodes)
   6.1 New AMI compatible with target k8s version
   6.2 Same labels & taints

7. Cordon & Drain Old Nodes
   7.1 cordon - make node as unschedulable, uncordon - make node as schedulable, drain - evict all pods from the node - subject PDB.
   kubectl cordon <node>
   kubectl drain <node> --ignore-daemonsets --delete-emptydir-data

   [Gracefully reschedules pods to new nodes]
   Delete old node group

8. Upgrade Add-ons
   VPC CNI, kube-proxy, CoreDNS, CSI drivers (EBS/EFS), Metrics server, Ingress controller.
 

